105. AIM’s impact is hard to gauge, but it must be recognized as only a
part of a larger corporate-right-wing campaign of attack. It has common
funding sources with such components of the conservative labyrinth as
AEI, Hoover, the Institute for Contemporary Studies, and others (see
Saloma, _Ominous Politics_, esp. chapters 2, 3, and 6), and has its own
special role to play. AIM’s head, Reed Irvine, is a frequent participant
in television talk shows, and his letters to the editor and commentary
are regularly published in the mass media. The media feel obligated to
provide careful responses to his detailed attacks on their news and
documentaries, and the Corporation for Public Broadcasting even helped
fund his group’s reply to the PBS series on Vietnam. His ability to get
the publisher of the _New York Times_ to meet with him personally once a
year—a first objective of any lobbyist—is impressive testimony to
influence. On his contribution to the departure of Raymond Bonner from
the _Times_, see Wolf, “Accuracy in Media Rewrites News and History,”
pp. 32–33.

