61. Based on conversations with voters, the Long group states that “most
people waited these long hours because of their desire to have their
_cedula_ stamped and their finger inked to avoid fines for not voting
and/or possible reprisals from the government and military.…” They note
that at many places voting officials stamped the _cedulas_ of those
unable to vote because of crowding just so they could leave (ibid., p.
6).

62. In the July 1, 1984, election for a constituent assembly, null and
blank votes exceeded those of any party and were a staggering 26 percent
of the total.

