_Towards a New Cold War_, chapter 5. Lewy tacitly concedes the accuracy
of this critique by evasion; compare the review with his response to
critics, _Washington Quarterly_ (Autumn 1979). For further insight into
the commitments and intellectual level of a man taken seriously as a
scholar, see his discussion of the need for the state to take stern
action to protect the public from “lies” by subversives, and to ensure
that the public is not deceived by the “hidden agenda” of such groups as
Clergy and Laity Concerned, the Coalition for a New Foreign and Military
Policy, NACLA, and others who seek to conceal “their espousal of
Cuban-style Communism” and who are engaged in “deception” and
“subversion.” As he correctly notes, and inadvertently reveals in his
discussion, “to totalitarianism, an opponent is by definition
subversive” (Lewy, “Does America Need a Verfassungsschutzbericht?”
_Orbis_ [Fall 1987]—a respected journal with a distinguished editorial
board).

34. Unpublished memorandum on pacification problems circulated within
